data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically on .NET 8. **No migration is needed for Thread.Abort.**

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would be to replace manual `Thread` usage with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` and better thread pool utilization — without ever needing `Thread.Abort`.
